	pages = {},
	doi = {10.1109/SITA67914.2025.11273691},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105030439339&doi=10.1109%2FSITA67914.2025.11273691&partnerID=40&md5=c6bf3bfa2786ced12caccc54a328ac51},
	affiliations = {RITM Laboratory CED Engineering Sciences, Hassan II University, Casablanca, Morocco; Mathematics, Data Science and Emerging Technologies Laboratory, Hassan I University, Settat, Morocco},
	abstract = {Mental disorders are being increasingly prevalent globally due to social, environmental and digital causes. Despite this increase, availability of specialized clinical care has not kept pace in most parts of the world. Fortunately, this is occurring at the same time of the advancement of large language models (LLMs), a form of artificial-intelligence, which have demonstrated intriguing potential for screening, diagnostic support, and therapeutic interactions. To examine this potential in more depth, we described and analyzed 41 studies that used transformer-based LLMs across psychiatry and clinical psychology that we located in the published literature between January 2022 and May 2025. We retrieved the literature through five open-access databases: Scopus, arXiv, Google Scholar, JMIR, and the ACM Digital Library. We extracted the following key variables from each article: Task type, target condition, model used, reported performance, and observed limitations. The most frequent tasks studied were detection of disorders and screening, decision-support and prevention. Reviewed papers mainly focused on depression and suicidality. GPT‑4 and GPT‑3.5 were the two most used models. Reported performance metrics, including overall accuracy and robustness, showed significant variability across tasks and datasets. Commonly described limitations were small or synthetic datasets, limited external validation, no real-world trials yet identified, and varying levels of transparency when reporting models' internal functioning. While LLMs may have promising capabilities, their full integration into clinical environments will have to contend with concerns about reliability, generalizability, and ethical use. Future research studies must conceptualize longitudinal studies, develop tools with the input of mental health professionals, and provide clarity in how safety, fairness, and data management are measured. ©2025 IEEE.},
