	affiliations = {Department of Computer Science, Wenzhou-Kean University, 88 Daxue Rd, Ouhai, Zhejiang, Wenzhou, 325060, China; Department of Computer Science, Kean University, 1000 Morris Avenue, Union, 07083, NJ, United States; Department of Computer Science, Brock University, 1812 Sir Isaac Brock Way, St. Catharines, L2S 3A1, ON, Canada; Nanjing University of Posts and Telecommunications, 9 Wenyuan Road, Jiangsu, Nanjing, 210023, China; Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Center, Wenzhou-Kean University, 88 Daxue Rd, Ouhai, Zhejiang, Wenzhou, 325060, China},
	abstract = {Federated Learning (FL) offers a decentralized paradigm for multi-class brain tumor classification using Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI), yet its clinical deployment is challenged by data scarcity, statistical heterogeneity (i.e., non-independent and identically distributed (non-IID) data), and strict privacy regulations. Standard FL algorithms often diverge under extreme single-class client partitions common in specialized medical centers. To address these barriers, we propose a robust, data-centric FL framework that bridges algorithmic limitations and clinical reality. The framework introduces a three-tier protocol: (i) an independent and identically distributed (IID) baseline; (ii) a Hybrid Federated Learning (Hybrid-FL) strategy using minimal shared clinical data to establish realistic performance upper bounds; and (iii) a Synthetic Federated Learning (Synthetic-FL) strategy leveraging Latent Diffusion Models (LDMs) for strictly privacy-preserving data augmentation. To mitigate confirmation bias in synthetic generation, we implement a multi-dimensional quality assurance protocol validating anatomical fidelity and diversity via Kernel Inception Distance (KID) and Learned Perceptual Image Patch Similarity (LPIPS) metrics. Experimental results on a large multi-institutional dataset (N=7,023) show that Hybrid-FL achieves high diagnostic accuracy (≈95%) with only 10% shared holdout data, while fully privacy-preserving Synthetic-FL recovers substantial performance (>83%) from a baseline of non-convergence without exposing patient records. Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM) confirms that the global model consistently captures robust pathological features across heterogeneous clients. This study quantitatively characterizes the privacy–utility trade-off and provides a scalable, interpretable engineering solution for collaborative neuro-oncology. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd.},
