	abstract = {Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) hemodynamic parameters are critical indicators of tumor aggressiveness and growth. However, their estimation is often hindered by low reliability, high bias, and extensive data processing time, and is dependent on operator experience. To address these challenges, we propose a versatile end-to-end framework (VEFAME) that integrates synthetic data-driven learning and spatial information for accurate and efficient estimation of MRI hemodynamic parameters, eliminating the need for explicit arterial input function (AIF) selection. Synthetic data used in VEFAME feature accurate AIFs, smooth residue functions, precise labels and spatial information incorporating local smoothness and complex texture priors. The efficacy of VEFAME is evaluated through both dynamic susceptibility contrast (DSC) and dynamic contrast-enhanced (DCE) MRI parameter estimation of numerical brain phantom and in vivo brain. Experimental results demonstrate that VEFAME improves the accuracy, precision, diagnostic value, and reliability of estimated MRI hemodynamic parameters. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd},
