	abstract = {Thyroid Cancer is a disease in which malignant (cancer) cells form in the tissues of the thyroid gland. Thyroid cancer is a prevalent endocrine malignancy, and early detection is crucial for improving patient outcomes. Predictive modeling has emerged as a valuable tool in diagnosing thyroid cancer, leveraging machine learning techniques for accurate classification. However, imbalanced datasets where malignant cases significantly outnumber benign ones can lead to biased predictions. This study explores the effectiveness of ensemble models in thyroid cancer prediction while addressing data imbalance through various balancing techniques. Ensemble learning, which combines multiple classifiers, enhances predictive performance by mitigating the limitations of individual models. Methods such as oversampling, under sampling, and synthetic data generation via SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique) are employed to create a balanced dataset, ensuring robust model training. Comparative analysis of ensemble approaches, including Random Forest, Extreme Gradient Boosting, demonstrates improved sensitivity and specificity. Experimental results indicate that integrating data balancing strategies with ensemble models significantly enhances diagnostic accuracy, offering a promising avenue for automated thyroid cancer recurrence detection. This research underscores the importance of balanced datasets and ensemble methodologies in medical prognostics, paving the way for reliable and interpretable predictive models in clinical applications. XGB achieved the lowest log loss among all ensemble models evaluated in this study, with a value of 0.1178 and training and testing accuracy of 100% and 97.4% respectively, underscoring its reliability in Thyroid Cancer Recurrence Prediction. Model performance is systematically assessed, with Xtreme Gradient Boosting (XGB) emerging as the top-performing algorithm. Its feature contributions are subsequently interpreted using LIME and SHAP.  © 2025 IEEE.},
